# One Function, Many Jobs

Having a function that always does the exact same thing is okay:
```javascript
function sayHappyBirthday() {
  console.log("Happy Birthday to you!");
}
```

But what if we want to sing to a *specific* person? Or add two *different* numbers together? 

We need a way to pass information INTO the function when we call it. We do this using **Parameters** and **Arguments**.

## Setting Up The Catchers Mitt

When we build (define) the function, we put variables inside the parentheses `()`. These are called **Parameters**.

Think of them as empty "catchers mitts" waiting to receive data.

```javascript
// 'name' is the parameter
function greetUser(name) {
  console.log("Welcome Back, " + name + "!");
}
```

Inside the function, we just use `name` like any normal variable!

## Throwing the Ball

When we *call* the function, we put the actual data inside the parentheses `()`. This data is called an **Argument**.

Think of the Argument as the baseball being thrown into the Parameter's mitt.

```javascript
// "Alice" is the Argument!
greetUser("Alice");

// We can reuse the same machine with different data!
greetUser("Bob");
```

The output will be `Welcome Back, Alice!` and then `Welcome Back, Bob!`.

slides.codeSnippet:
// This machine needs TWO pieces of data
function printEnemyDamage(enemyName, damage) {
  console.log(enemyName + " took " + damage + " damage!");
}

// Provide both arguments in the same order
printEnemyDamage("Orc", 50);
printEnemyDamage("Dragon", 9000);

